Motivation¶

The United States has one of the highest rates of road accidents in the world, with over 40,000 fatalities and millions of injuries each year. These accidents have a devastating impact on individuals, families, and communities, and they also have a significant economic cost, with billions of dollars in medical expenses and lost productivity.

One way to address this problem is to develop a road accidents model that can help identify the factors that contribute to accidents and predict the likelihood of future accidents in different areas. This model could be used by policymakers and transportation agencies to target interventions and invest in safety measures that can prevent accidents and save lives.

The motivation for designing such a model is twofold. First, it would help to better understand the causes of road accidents and identify opportunities for intervention. By analyzing data on factors such as weather, road conditions, and road obstacles, the model could provide insights into the underlying causes of accidents and help identify interventions that can reduce their frequency.

Second, the model could be used to predict the likelihood of accidents in different areas, which could help to prioritize safety investments and allocate resources more effectively. By providing a quantitative assessment of the risk of accidents in different areas, the model could help policymakers and transportation agencies make more informed decisions about where to invest in safety measures such as improved signage, enhanced road maintenance, and driver education programs.

Overall, the motivation for designing a road accidents model is to help prevent accidents, save lives, and reduce the economic cost of accidents in the United States. By providing insights into the causes of accidents and predicting their likelihood in different areas, such a model could play a valuable role in improving road safety and protecting the public.

U.S. Accidents (2016 - 2021) Data¶

This dataset contains countrywide traffic accident records that cover 49 states of the United States happened between 2016 and 2021. The data captures the geographic location, time, and severity of accidents, as well as a variety of weather conditions and road features where those accidents occurred, which we will use as features for our machine learning modeling later in this project to predict the severity of accidents. For example, temperature, visibility of the road, presence of road obstacles (such as stops, bumps, crossing, junction, etc.), or period of a day when an accident happened. In the following section, we preprocess this dataset to allow us better extract useful information for EDA, and prepare for choosing relevant features for modeling.

Data sources:

  1. Moosavi, Sobhan, Mohammad Hossein Samavatian, Srinivasan Parthasarathy, and Rajiv Ramnath. A Countrywide Traffic Accident Dataset., 2019.

  2. Moosavi, Sobhan, Mohammad Hossein Samavatian, Srinivasan Parthasarathy, Radu Teodorescu, and Rajiv Ramnath. "Accident Risk Prediction based on Heterogeneous Sparse Data: New Dataset and Insights." In proceedings of the 27th ACM SIGSPATIAL International Conference on Advances in Geographic Information Systems, ACM, 2019.

Link to the Kaggle dataset: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sobhanmoosavi/us-accidents?fbclid=IwAR0b78zhjpAcm3WpxPdyX9lppRxY7GMDsctVvDgDHmv4m4U4VtVniWI-W88

3. Drop Irrelevant Columns and Rename Columns¶

Since all of the accidents recorded in this dataset happened in the U.S., the Country column is not informative for our EDA or modeling. We are going to drop it. The number columm that refers to the street number where an accident occurred doesn't seem to provide any information in predicting the severity of accidents, so we will also procede to drop the column. In addition, we are going to drop Civil_Twilight, Nautical_Twilight, and Astronomical_Twilight columns, which store day/night information using different definitions, because we have another equivalent and more straighforward column Sunset_Sunrise that we can utilize in our EDA. We also dropped the features Airport_code and Timezone because the same information relating to location of the accident can be found using the column City instead. We also dropped multiple road feature columns because we discovered that all of the features had a false value, thus it was not meaningful to keep the columns. Lastly, we dropped the columns weather_timestamp and description because both weather_timestamp and description were columns that were used to create additional columns for the dataset in the first place. For instance, the weather_timestamp allowed the dataset to find the weather at the time of the accident, and the column description allowed the dataset to generate columns such as accident location. Since we have new columns that better represent the original data, we can drop these rows as well.

In [ ]:
# drop irrelevant columns

5. Preprocess Accident Datetime, Weather Condition, and Street¶

Accident Datetime Parsing¶

Since we want to use the Start_Time and End_Time columns for our EDA, we need to extract the day, month, and year for each accident and calculate the duration of each accident.

In [ ]:
# extracting day, month, year, and day of a week to separate columns
df['Year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Start_Time']).year
df['Month'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Start_Time']).month
df['Day'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Start_Time']).day
df['Day_of_Week'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df['Start_Time']).dayofweek + 1

# calculate accident duration using Start_Time and End_Time
df['Duration'] = df['End_Time'] - df['Start_Time']

# convert the duration to minutes
df['Duration_Minutes']=round(df['Duration']/np.timedelta64(1,'m'))

Weather Condition Parsing¶

Looking at the weather conditions column, we see that there are 128 unique weather patterns, which is too many to perform efficient EDA and modeling on. Thus, we grouped the weather conditions into 10 large categories that well represents the different categories that the weather conditions fall in. We used nltk to tokenize the weather conditions, and matched specific keywoards to the tokenized result in order to sort the weather. For certain extreme weather such as tornado, hurricane..etc, we grouped them into the 'Other' category.

In [ ]:
# A look at the count of unique weather values.
df['Weather_Condition'].nunique()
Out[ ]:
128
In [ ]:
# Setting up weather condition categories
weather_features = ['Drizzle', 'Rain', 'Snow', 'Cloudy', 'Fog', 'Haze', 'Windy', 'Thunderstorm', 'Fair', 'Other']

# Function for categorizing weather conditions
def weather(content):
  token = nltk.word_tokenize(content)
  for word in token:
    if word in weather_features:
      return word
    if word == 'nan':
      return 'Fair'
    if word == 'Thunder':
      return 'Thunderstorm'
  return 'Other'

# Apply function to weather condition column to categorize weather 
df['Weather_Condition'] = df['Weather_Condition'].apply(lambda x : weather(x))

Before we continue on to EDA, we would like to fill in the missing data in our dataset. For quantitative features like the ones in the cell directly below, we chose to fill the missing data with the mean of the dataset. While there might be other methods such as kNN imputation that might lead to more accurate results, due to the large dataset size we have of > 2M data samples, this was the most efficient method that we chose for filling in missing data.

Feature Engineering¶

Create a New Column: Height¶

Looking through the environment features in our dataset, we thought the air pressure information (Pressure) would potentially give us more insight if transformed to height information when we look at the correlation between accident severity and it later. So we created a new feature Height by calculating directly from the air pressure feature using a standard conversion formula.

In [ ]:
# Convert temperature (F) to Kelvin unit (K)
df['Temperature_K'] = ((df['Temperature']-32)*5/9) + 273.15

# Find height above sea level in feet
df['Height'] = -(1.38*10**-23 * df['Temperature_K'] * np.log(df['Pressure']/29.92))/(4.8107*10**(-26)*9.81) 

# Change meters to feet
df['Height'] = df['Height'] * 3.28084  

# Sort the data based on height and take a sneak peak of the height info
df.sort_values(by='Height', ascending=False)

Create a New Column: Obstacle¶

Since there are many different types of road features such as crossing, junction, traffic signal etc, it may be beneficial to create a seperate column that determines whether a road feature exists or not. Specifically, for the purpose of selecting road features that may have an impact on traffic accidents, we've chosen to categorize accidents that has any one of the below road features as being near an obstacle when the accident happened.

  • Crossing: Refers to any crossing across roads for pedestrians, cyclists, etc.
  • Junction: Refers to any highway ramp, exit, or entrance.
  • No_Exit: Indicates there is no possibility to travel further by any transport mode along a formal path or route.
  • Railway: Indicates the presence of railways.
  • Roundabout: Refers to a circular road junction.
  • Stop: Refers to stop sign.
  • Traffic_Signal: Refers to traffic signal on intersections.
In [ ]:
#Selecting road features 
df['Obstacle'] = df[['Crossing','Junction', 'Railway', 'Stop', 
                     'Traffic_Signal']].any(axis=1)
#Giving it a value of 0 or 1
df[['Obstacle']] = df[['Obstacle']].astype(int)

Road Features Encoding¶

The following cell converts categorical variables (boolean type features) that tell whether there exists certain road features in the road where an accident happened, into a binary value of 1 or 0.

In [ ]:
# convert boolean type columns to integer, which results in assigning each value to 1 or 0
df[['Amenity', 'Crossing', 'Junction', \
    'Railway', 'Station', 'Stop', \
    'Traffic_Signal']] \
    = df[['Amenity', 'Crossing', 'Junction',\
          'Railway', 'Station', 'Stop', \
          'Traffic_Signal']].astype(int)

Street Parsing¶

Looking at the street column, there are currently too many street names to perform efficient EDA and modeling on. However, the street feature could be useful in our project since it gives insight on the type of road the accident happend on. Thus, we created a new column called Street Type that categorizes the street as either highway or local road based on the street name.

In [ ]:
#Helper arrays for categorizing streets 
highways = ['Fwy', 'Expy', 'Highway', 'Hwy', 'Route']
local_roads = ['Rd', 'Ave','Blvd', 'Road']

#Function for categorizing streets as highway or local roads
def street_type(street):
  if street[:1] == 'I' or street[2:3] == '-':
    return 'Interstate'
  if street[-2:] == 'Rd' or 'St':
    return 'Local Roads'
  for highway in highways:
    if highway in street:
      return 'Interstate'
  for local in local_roads:
    if local in street:
      return 'Local Roads'
  return 'Other'
  
#Apply function on 'Street' column and create a new column called 'Street Type'
df['Street_Type'] = df['Street'].apply(lambda x : street_type(x))
df_categorical = df

Day-Night Encoding¶

The Sunrise_Sunset column contains information on whether an accident happened during the day or at night. Since we want to use this column in our ML modeling, we convert it into a binary value of 1 or 0.

In [ ]:
# we assigned "Day" to 0 and "Night" to 1
def encoding(x):
  code = {"Day": 0, "Night": 1}
  return code[x]

df['Sunrise_Sunset'] = df['Sunrise_Sunset'].apply(lambda x: encoding(x))

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

Time and Location of the Accidents¶

To understand our dataset a bit more, we looked at different features in our dataset, their distribution, correlation, as well as any other information that was of interest to us.

The first feature we looked at was accident count by State, because we were interested to see the geographic locations of different accidents. The graph shows that California and Florida have the most accident count by states, which is expected since it is known that the two States have the most amount of traffic and commuting.

In [ ]:
#selecting state and id features and sorting it by state in alphabetical order
hist_states_df = df[["State", "ID"]].sort_values(by="State")

#setting up chart features

plt.title("Accident Count by State", fontsize=18) 

#plot the countplot
hist_states = sns.countplot(x = "State", data = hist_states_df, palette="GnBu");

Next, we looked at accident count by month and by day of week to see the accident distribution across different time periods. Interestingly, as shown in the graph, December has the most accident count out of all the Months. We hypothesize that this is due to December being a high season for travelling. Another reason could be due to the winter months causing more traffic accidents due to severe weather. However, that is probably not entirely the case since the months of November - Feburary should have similar weather patterns overall.

In [ ]:

The graph below shows that weekdays (Monday - Friday) have the highest number of accident counts. This is something expected because lots of people commute to work or school on the weekdays so the traffic flow is naturally larger on the weekdays, leading to more accidents.

Accidents during the Day vs Night¶

Another feature we were interested in looking deeper into was daylight. While there would definitely be more accidents that happened during the day since traffic flow is naturally larger during the day, we were interested in seeing how daylight together with weather, obstacle, or other features might influence accident count. For example, we hypothesize that since road visibility is worse at night, perhaps a rainy night would lead to a higher accident percentage than during the day. Similarily, perhaps certain obstacles at night would lead to a higher accident percentage whereas other obstacles during the day would lead to a higher accident percentage.

Day vs Night by Weather¶

The graph below shows the distribution of weather types for accidents happening during the day and during the night. Even though the monthly data doesn't suggest that seaonal weather like snow have a strong impact on the number of accident counts, we are still interested in seeing the relationship between different types of weather, especially how it relates to daylight.

In [ ]:
#seperate data into day and night 
day_df = df[df['Sunrise_Sunset'] == 0].reset_index()
night_df = df[df['Sunrise_Sunset'] == 1].reset_index()

#creating weather dataset for day
weather_percentage_day = day_df[['Weather_Condition', 'ID']].groupby('Weather_Condition').count().reset_index()
weather_percentage_day = weather_percentage_day.rename(columns={"Weather_Condition": "Weather", "ID" : "Count"})
weather_percentage_day['Percentage'] = round((weather_percentage_day['Count']/ weather_percentage_day['Count'].sum())*100, 2)
weather_percentage_day['Daylight'] = 'Day'

#creating weather dataset for night
weather_percentage_night = night_df[['Weather_Condition', 'ID']].groupby('Weather_Condition').count().reset_index()
weather_percentage_night = weather_percentage_night.rename(columns={"Weather_Condition": "Weather", "ID" : "Count"})
weather_percentage_night['Percentage'] = round((weather_percentage_night['Count']/ weather_percentage_night['Count'].sum())*100, 2)
weather_percentage_night['Daylight'] = 'Night'

#concat the two datasets
weather_percentage = pd.concat([weather_percentage_day, weather_percentage_night], axis=0)

#plot
plt.figure(figsize=(15,8))
g = sns.barplot(x="Weather", y='Percentage', hue="Daylight", data=weather_percentage, palette="GnBu")
plt.title("Accident Percentage by Weather and Daylight", fontsize=14)

#plot datapoints
xaxis = np.arange(10)
for i,j in zip(xaxis, weather_percentage[weather_percentage['Daylight'] == 'Day']['Percentage']):
    g.annotate(str(j), xy=(i - 0.35,j + 0.5))

for i,j in zip(xaxis, weather_percentage[weather_percentage['Daylight'] == 'Night']['Percentage']):
    g.annotate(str(j), xy=(i + 0.05,j + 0.5))

plt.show()

As the graph above shows, a large majority of accidents happened on a fair or cloudy day regardless of the time of day, which is something we expected because fair and cloudy are the most frequent types of weather patterns in the U.S. However, if we look closely at how each weather relates to daylight, we see that fair, fog, and snow weather takes up a slightly larger percentage of accidents that happened at night vs during the day.

If a larger percentage of accidents that happened at night happened during a fair day, perhaps it suggests that there are other factors aside from weather relating to daylight that influences the number of accidents. We could also infer that more accidents that happen at night are of the result of a snowy day. However, the same cannot be said about fog because as shown in the graph below, fog naturally happens during dusk hours. Thus, the graph below serves as a simple sanity check on the relationships between daylight and weather by showing what weather is the most common during what time of the day.

Day vs Night by Road Features¶

Aside from weather, we were also interested in looking at how daylight relates to obstacles. The graph below shows the percentage of accidents that happened near an obstacle vs not near an obstacle for all accidents, daytime accidents, and night time accidents. We see that overall, only a quarter of accidents happened near an obstacle, which is again, something that we expected since naturally most accidents just happen on the streets and not necessarily 'near' something. The graph also doesn't seem to show much discrepancy between the distribution for day and night time accidents.

plt.show()

If we dig a bit deeper and look at the different types of obstacles and how they relate to daylight, we see that while accidents happening near junctions and stop signs take up a slightly larger percentage of total night time accidents and accidents that happen near traffic signals and crossing take up a slightly larger percentage of total daytime accidents, there isn't much difference between the distributions for daytime and night time accidents. Thus, we don't seem to see much relationship between how road features have an impact on whether an accident is more likely to happen during the day or night.

Severity Distribution Analysis¶

In addition to correlation, we are also interested in seeing how accident severity relates to different features. Accident severity is defined as the extent to which an accident impacts the traffic flow. However, as shown by the graph below that shows the accident counts by severity, it's clear that we have an class imbalance in our dataset with most of the accidents having a severity level of 2. This issue was addressed earlier by taking a subsample of the data set for our machine learning models instead of using the imbalanced dataset we have here. For the purpose of EDA, instead of looking at counts, we again took percentages of the different severity to compare the different features.

plt.show()

We looked at how the existence vs absence of an obstacle nearby may relate to the severity level of the accident. Interestingly, the distribution is flipped for severity level 1, with the majoriy of the accidents happening near an obstacle. Perhaps this could mean that obstacles such as stop signs, traffic lights, and crossing could've induced the driver to slow down, leading to less severe accidents. Another hypothesis could be that accidents that happen near obstacles are more likely to happen on local roads instead of interstates. This could mean that driving speeds are naturally slower, so the accidents would be less severe. This could also mean that if an accident happens on the interstate vs local roads, accidents on interstates may more easily block the traffic since there is only one road whereas even if an accident happens on a local road, cars have other roads to take and navigate away from the accident. Since severity of an accident is based on how much traffic trouble the accident caused, this could be one of the reasons why severity level 1 has such a high percentage of accidents happening near obstacles.

Severity Correlation Analysis¶

We would like to visualize the correlations between the severity of accidents and any other numeric features in our data such as temperature, wind chill, visibility, and etc. It would be useful to know whether there is any strong correlation between a particular feature and the severity of accdients when we do the modeling below.

We started by creating a group of all numeric feature variables from our dataset and Severity, and create a correlation matrix using this dataframe. We used three different methods to calculate correlations - Pearson, Spearman, and Kendall - as we intended to catch any correlations as possible.

1. Correlation Heatmap - Pearson¶

In [ ]:
numerics_df = df[['Severity', 'Start_Lat', 'Start_Lng', 'End_Lat', 'End_Lng', 'Distance','Temperature', \
                  'Wind_Chill', 'Humidity', 'Pressure', 'Visibility', 'Wind_Speed', 'Precipitation']]
In [ ]:
# create a correlation matrix and visualize it using correlation heatmap

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))

plt.title("Severity Correlation - Pearson", fontsize=18) 
plt.show()

The correlation heatmap above does not give us many significant highlights. There doesn't seem to be a clear relationship between Severity and the selected features. We noticed there are perfect (or almost perfect) correlations between latitudes and longitudes related features, and temperature and wind chill, which are both self-explanatory. We will consider removing the end latitude and end longitudes features for our modeling later. Humidity and temperature, humidity and wind chill are also fairly correlated with coefficients of -0.5 and -0.48 respectively.

The main reason why we extracted the non-imputed data as the machine learning dataset is twofold:

1) The imputation done on the original dataset is a mean imputation. This meant the data will be more biased towards a specific value and less representative of the true dataset. The original dataset is used for EDA. By doing the KNN imputation here, we can assure that the machine learning model is running on the more accurate dataset.

2) It is VERY expensive to copy the original dataframe without the imputation. Having 2 dataframes with over 2 million datapoints and over 30 features is not ideal for colab. It is more cost efficient to take a subset from the original dataframe to calculate. The good thing here we needed to undersample the overbearing bucket of 2 from the target feature, so taking a subset was the right call.

PCA Dimensionality Reduction¶

We make PCA dataset here to be used in future modeling. By following closely with class homework, we first fit a pca to the number of features. Then we plot the explained variance vs number of components to get the ratio in order to find the optimal number of components needed to keep above 90 percent of explained variance. In the end, we settled for 8 components differed from the 12 features we have before.

PCA is also very useful when trying to fix overfitting and run long models. PCA'ed datasets are simpler than its original dataset, thus it'll tend towards less variance and improve the overfitted data. Also, running long models on PCA will always be faster than running models on the original dataset (just because there are less features in the PCA dataset)

Ideal components tuning¶

DummyClassifier¶

We created some baseline tests with the sklearn dummy classifier library. Each strategy are naive ways of predicting the target. For example, the most_frequent classifier would choose the most frequent label (in this case it would be any of the 4, because they are distributed equally per how we chose the dataset). We use these tests as baselines of what kind of f1/accuracy scores we are shooting for.

Logistic Regression Model¶

Logistic Modeling is the most basic type of modeling for classification. In this case, we want to target the severity of road accidents, which is seperated into 4 classification : 1,2,3, and 4. Each number is how severe the accident is, and is pre determined by the person who created the dataset.

We tuned the hyper parameters with gridsearchCV, where it will check all the possible combinations of the hyperparameters we give it and find the best accuracy score from the model based on a cross validation test. The reason why we use macro here is because according to the sk learn page, macro is best used for balanced datasets. Also, the reason why we only had 1 penalties because lbfgs can only run l2 regularization.

We found the best hyperparameters to be C = 10, Ridge Regression, and a newton-cg solver. This indicates that the dataset have features that are significantly more important than other features.

After plugging in the hyperparameters into the model, we get a training score to be 0.44, an accuracy score to be 0.44 and a f1 score to be 0.43. This would indicate underfitting, as it's still predicting only 40% right. However, it is already a significantly better predictor than the dummy classifier.

KNN Model¶

KNN modeling is a lazy model used to predict classification problems too. What lazy means is that the model memorizes the data instead of actually building a model with weights. This makes it very easy to implement and understand. However, the trade off is that it becomes computationally expensive when it needs to predict something, since it needs to take a poll of all the points around it.

KNN is used here because its another way to model this classification problem. Its also fairly inexpensive to run.

With the only hyperparameter to tune to be neighbors, we find that a n neighbor of 9 is best for our purposes. Notice here we also use a macro scoring for f1 because the data, as said before, is balanced. We will be using macro scoring for f1 for all of the models.

Our result actually surprised us a little. It actually outperformed logistic regression getting a training score of 0.61, an accuracy score of 0.52, and a f1 score of 0.51. Although its a bit overfitted, I think this is still a model worth looking at more closely in the future

Decision Trees Models¶

The last model considered in this report is a decision tree. A decision tree is a fantastic way to model classification problems. Decision trees are used when there is a non linear boundary between the classes(as oppose to logistic regression where the predictor is a line). However one trouble with a decision tree is that it is prone to over fitting, and the calculations are long.

After many hyperparameters tuning, we find that the best hyperparameters are splitter = best, max depth = none, min sample leaf = 5, and min sample split = 5.

We can see that we get another good result(albeit a bit overfitted). The training accuracy is 0.68, the test accuracy is 0.63, and the f1 score is 0.62. This is our best performing model by far, but its still a long way of being a model.

Conclusion¶

EDA¶

From the exploratory data analysis, we were able to better understand our dataset and gain some insights about traffic accidents in the United States.

First, we saw that California and Florida had the most number of accidents out of all the states and that December had the most number of accidents out of all the months. We also saw how time of the day and day of the week relates to accident counts, with the rush hour times having drastically more accidents. These findings reiterate the fact that higher traffic flows naturally leads to more traffic accidents, and while there may be other factors like visibility, weather, or road features that could impact traffic accident frequency, ultimately, the biggest influencing factor is the amount of traffic on the road.

Looking at other factors like daylight, weather, road features and how they relate to the count and severity of traffic accidents, we saw that while weather by itself doesnt seem to have a strong impact on the number of traffic accidents, certain weather such as snow when combined with poor visibility at night could potentially increase the chance of a traffic accident. Additionally, while weather might not have a strong impact on increasing or decreasing accident counts, it appears to have a slight relationship with the severity of accidents seeing that severity 1 and 2 accidents follow a similar weather pattern distribution whereas severity 3 and 4 have a more similar distribution. We also found that the majority of the accidents with a severity level 1 happened near an obstacle, which suggests that certain road features may influence the severity level of accidents. However, the same cannot be said about the relationship between obstacles and weather or time of day, since we couldn't find any conclusive relationship in our EDA.

Overall, while there are some minimal insights from our EDA portion, it seems as if many of the features are intercorrelated with each other, and that there isnt one specific feature that has a great impact on accident count or severity level.

Taking a further look at the correlation heatmap further demonstrates that there isnt one specific feature that relates to severity level of the accidents. The features that show a strong correlation in our heatmap are features that are inherently related to one another such as longitude and latitude, traffic signal and crossing, and height and pressure. Thus, while we were able to find some relationships between our features, we werent able to find any clear relationship between how a feature may impact the severity of accidents.

Modeling¶

From the modeling data, we could see that there are stark improvements in the modeling that we did. From the beginning, we had a dummy classifier that had an accuracy score of 0.25, which makes sense because the labels in the target feature is evenly divided up by 4. By doing two iterations with different number of data points and different parameters, we came to the conclusion below:

  • Logistic Regression: The first result of logistic regression returned an accuracy score of 0.44 and a f1 score of 0.43. This is a bit better than just randomly guessing, but its still severely underfitted. To improve our score, we used more data points in the second iteration and also 6 new categorical features that added to the complexity of the model. We can see an improvement in the second iteration where the accuracy score is 0.48 and the f1 score is also 0.48.

  • KNN: The first result of KNN returned an accuracy score of 0.52 and an f1 score of 0.51. However, it also had a training accuracy of 0.62, which means the model is overfitting. However, we cannot deny that this model outperform logistic regression by a bit. To fix the overfitting in the model, our second iteration called for the n_neighbors to be higher. Increasing n_neighbors will decrease the noise that comes from small nearest neighbor values. Also including the categorical data means the model will be more complex. We found that the second iteration did indeed improve the model to a 0.57 accuracy and 0.56 f1 score with the training accuracy dropping to 0.6.

  • Decision Trees: The initial result of decsion trees was a 0.63 accuracy score and a 0.63 f1 score. However, this came with a training accuracy of 0.69, which proved to be a little overfitted. To combat this overfitting, we tried to use random forest, but unfortunately got a result that was even more overfitted (training: 0.93 test: 0.68). For our second iteration of Decision Trees, we have new categorical data that helped smooth out the overfittedness of our original model, and end up with the best score of 0.66 testing accuracy and 0.65 f1 score.

In conclusion, the decision tree model presented in our project best models the US Road Accidents Dataframe, with a training accuracy of 0.66 and f1 score of 0.65.

Future Directions¶

There are quite a few directions this project can go from here, however, some of the biggest improvements this project can make are listed below:

  • Forward Feed Neural Network: A neural network is definitely possible with this dataset, especially with a dataset this big. A neural net would help with the overall underfitting of the models in this project. However, we do have to watch out for the computing power and the time it takes to run a neural network. Otherwise, a neural network would be a great addition to this project.

  • Gathering more data: Another way to solve the overall underfitted models in our project (to increase complexity) is to include more features in our dataset to run the machine learning models on. We could potentially find other datasets such as car density in each city as one of the features or the even the type of car that was in the accident. All these new features can add to the complexity of the model and help it get a better accuracy and f1 score

  • Better Hardware/Optimized Code: A problem we repeatedly encountered in this project was the fact that colab would keep crashing on us because there isn't enough RAM. We made some adjustments in the project like sampling only a small subset of data to be used in machine learning. However, with more RAM or a more optimized code, we would not have to worry about that.

  • A prediction tool: We could potentially even turn this project into a detection tool for predicting accidents in certain cities near certain features. This would require a lot more domain knowledge and more up to date data from around the US.
